p.text:
In general, the plaintiff must fairly inform the defendant of the nature and extent of the damages claimed, and if the claim is able to be precisely calculated, particulars should be given of the facts which make such a calculation possible: Perestrello e Companhia Lda v United Paint Co Ltd [1969] 3All ER 479; [1969] 1 WLR 570 ; see also Lachaume v Broughton (1903) 3 SR (NSW) 475 ; Illawarra Coke Co Ltd v Le Plastrier (1917) 34 WN (NSW) 23 and Domsalla v Barr [1969] 1 WLR 630; [1969] 3 All ER 487 . The rules specifically require particulars of out-of-pocket expenses (
r 15.6
), exemplary damages (
r 15.7
) and aggravated damages (
r 15.8
). In general, and subject to any order under 
r 15.10
, particulars are not required to be given of general damages: Singleton v John Fairfax & Sons Ltd (No 2) [1983] 2 NSWLR 728 at 730 . However, particulars are required of special damages (London & Northern Bank v George Newnes Ltd (1900) 16 TLR 433 ; Mills v Mills (1948) 65 WN (NSW) 115) which cannot be recovered unless pleaded: Ilkiw v Samuels [1963] 2 All ER 879; [1963] 1 WLR 991 .

It is not the function of particulars to fill material gaps in a statement of claim that does not disclose a cause of action, or otherwise fails to comply with the Rules: Bruce v Odhams Press Ltd [1936] 1 KB 697 at 712 ; Pinson v Lloyds and National Provincial Foreign Bank Ltd [1941] 2 KB 72 at 75; [1941] 2 All ER 636 ; H 1976 Nominees Pty Ltd v Galli (1979) 30 ALR 181 at 186–7; 40 FLR 242 . Particulars, as distinct from pleaded allegations, are not required to be traversed (see 
r 14.26
) and a party need not (and generally should not — having regard to the requirements of brevity) plead to particulars: Pinson v Lloyds and National Provincial Foreign Bank Ltd, above; Chapple v Electrical Trades Union [1961] 3 All ER 612; [1961] 1 WLR 1290 . Because particulars operate as a complement to, and not a substitute for, properly pleaded allegations, a party ought not set out to achieve the effect of amending a pleading by purporting merely to give additional particulars. This involves attempting to ignore the rules requiring the filing of an amended pleading, pursuant to which the party seeking such amendment must, depending on the circumstances, seek either the consent of the other parties or the leave of the court. Where particulars which are intended to have the practical effect of amending a pleading are accepted by an opposing party, the proceeding may be conducted on that basis. A party to whom particulars of that kind have been given might so conduct itself as to represent to the party giving the particulars that no objection would be taken to the case being conducted on the basis of them even though, strictly speaking, there should have been an amendment. In such circumstances, any objection taken later might be cured by the granting of the necessary amendments: Bruce v Odhams Press Ltd [1936] 1 KB 697 ; Southern Cross Exploration NL v Fire & All Risks Insurance Co Ltd (1985) 2 NSWLR 340 at 351 ; NRNQ v MEQ Nickel Pty Ltd [1991] 2 Qd R 592 at 597–8 ; Beach Petroleum NL v Johnson (1991) 105 ALR 456 .
